'''Moriya Yorizane''' (守矢 頼真, {{ill|Eishō 2|ja|永正2nd year|12=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|May 25 (lunar calendar)|ja|5月25日 (旧暦)|12=draft|12=draft}} [{{ill|June 26, 1505|ja|1505th year 6月26日|12=draft|12=draft}}] – {{ill|Keichō 2|ja|慶長2nd year|12=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|September 10 (lunar calendar)|ja|9月10日 (旧暦)|12=draft|12=draft}} [{{ill|October 20, 1597|ja|1597th year 10月20日|12=draft|12=draft}}]) was a {{ill|Shinto priest|ja|神職|12=draft|12=draft}} during the {{ill|Sengoku period (Japan)|ja|戦国時代 (日本)|12=draft|12=draft}}. He served as the {{ill|jinchōkan|ja|神長官|12=draft|12=draft}} (chief priest) of {{ill|Suwa Taisha|ja|諏訪大社|1=Suwa-taisha|12=draft|12=draft}} in the {{ill|Suwa District, Nagano|ja|諏訪郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Shinano Province|ja|信濃国|12=draft|12=draft}}. According to the *{{ill|Suwa Shiryō Sōsho|ja|諏訪史料叢書|12=draft|12=draft}}*<ref>諏訪史料叢書 諏訪教育会著 1925-1952 12巻 守矢頼真書留(守矢頼真) 神長殿知行御検地[https://iss.ndl.go.jp/sp/show/R100000002-I000000871552-00/ 国会図書館]</ref>, he was the son of {{ill|Moriya Ariyoshi|ja|守矢有実|12=draft|12=draft}}. His son was {{ill|Moriya Nobuzane|ja|守矢信真|12=draft|12=draft}}. His initial name was Yorimitsu<ref>[https://kotobank.jp/word/%E5%AE%88%E7%9F%A2%E9%A0%BC%E5%AE%9F-1794824 コトバンク守矢頼実]参照。</ref>.
== Biography == The {{ill|Moriya clan|ja|守矢氏|1=Moriya clan|12=draft|12=draft}} is believed to be descended from either {{ill|Moreya no Kami|ja|洩矢神|12=draft|12=draft}} or {{ill|Mononobe no Moriya|ja|物部守屋|12=draft|12=draft}}, but this remains uncertain. Yorizane served under the {{ill|Suwa clan|ja|諏訪氏|1=Suwa clan|12=draft|12=draft}}, the {{ill|Ōhori|ja|大祝|12=draft|12=draft}} (chief priests) of Suwa Taisha, and frequently clashed with the {{ill|Negi|ja|禰宜|12=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|tayū|ja|太夫|12=draft|12=draft}} Yajima Mitsukiyo. He was initially at a disadvantage but regained his position during the appointment of {{ill|Suwa Yoritaka|ja|諏訪頼高|12=draft|12=draft}} as Ōhori in {{ill|Tenbun 7|ja|天文7th year|12=draft|12=draft}} (1538). Yorizane also opposed {{ill|Suwa Yorishige (Sengoku period)|ja|諏訪頼重 (戦国時代)|12=draft|12=draft}} regarding taxation on Suwa Taisha.
In {{ill|Tenbun 11|ja|天文11th year|12=draft|12=draft}} (1542), when {{ill|Takeda Shingen|ja|Takeda Shingen|12=draft|12=draft}} of {{ill|Kai Province|ja|甲斐国|12=draft|12=draft}} initiated his invasion of Suwa, Yorishige was captured and later died. Yorizane supported the Takeda clan’s control of Suwa and earned their trust through rituals and prayers for victory (*{{ill|Moriya Yorizane Shokutō|ja|守矢頼真書留|12=draft|12=draft}}*). In {{ill|Eiroku 2|ja|永禄2nd year|12=draft|12=draft}} (1559), he retired and passed the role of jinchōkan to his son Nobuzane. After the fall of the Takeda clan, Yorizane worked to revive the Suwa clan and contributed to the restoration of Suwa Taisha.
== *Moriya Yorizane Shokutō* == A personal record written by Yorizane, comprising one volume, documents the rituals and management of Suwa Taisha from his father’s era. The surviving entries span from {{ill|Tenbun 11|ja|天文11th year|12=draft|12=draft}} (1542) to {{ill|Tenbun 21|ja|天文21st year|12=draft|12=draft}} (1552). It includes key historical events, such as the birth of Yorishige’s heir in April 1542 and Yorishige’s death in July. While it initially covers the Takeda invasion of Suwa, later entries focus on shrine administration. The original manuscript was preserved by the Moriya family, and its text has been reproduced in collections such as the *{{ill|Shinano Shiryō Sōsho|ja|信濃史料叢書|12=draft|12=draft}}* and the *{{ill|Yamanashi Prefectural History|ja|山梨県史|12=draft|12=draft}}*.
== *Shinshi Ontō no Nikki* == A record of the shrine's annual rituals and notable events from {{ill|Kyōroku 1|ja|享禄元年|12=draft|12=draft}} (1528) to {{ill|Tenbun 23|ja|天文23rd year|12=draft|12=draft}} (1554). It describes significant occurrences, such as the peace negotiations between Takeda Nobutora and Suwa Hekiunsai at the Sakai River in 1535, and events leading to Takeda Shingen's invasion of Suwa. While the original manuscript has not been located, a copy made in {{ill|Bunka 14|ja|文化14th year|12=draft|12=draft}} (1817) has been used for reproductions in historical collections.
