In {{ill|Tenbun 11|ja|天文11th year|12=draft}} (1542), when {{ill|Takeda Shingen|ja|Takeda Shingen|12=draft}} of {{ill|Kai Province|ja|甲斐国|12=draft}} initiated his invasion of Suwa, Yorishige was captured and later died. Yorizane supported the Takeda clan’s control of Suwa and earned their trust through rituals and prayers for victory (*{{ill|Moriya Yorizane Shokutō|ja|守矢頼真書留|12=draft}}*). In {{ill|Eiroku 2|ja|永禄2nd year|12=draft}} (1559), he retired and passed the role of jinchōkan to his son Nobuzane. After the fall of the Takeda clan, Yorizane worked to revive the Suwa clan and contributed to the restoration of Suwa Taisha.

== *Moriya Yorizane Shokutō* ==
A personal record written by Yorizane, comprising one volume, documents the rituals and management of Suwa Taisha from his father’s era. The surviving entries span from {{ill|Tenbun 11|ja|天文11th year|12=draft}} (1542) to {{ill|Tenbun 21|ja|天文21st year|12=draft}} (1552). It includes key historical events, such as the birth of Yorishige’s heir in April 1542 and Yorishige’s death in July. While it initially covers the Takeda invasion of Suwa, later entries focus on shrine administration. The original manuscript was preserved by the Moriya family, and its text has been reproduced in collections such as the *{{ill|Shinano Shiryō Sōsho|ja|信濃史料叢書|12=draft}}* and the *{{ill|Yamanashi Prefectural History|ja|山梨県史|12=draft}}*.

== *Shinshi Ontō no Nikki* ==
A record of the shrine's annual rituals and notable events from {{ill|Kyōroku 1|ja|享禄元年|12=draft}} (1528) to {{ill|Tenbun 23|ja|天文23rd year|12=draft}} (1554). It describes significant occurrences, such as the peace negotiations between Takeda Nobutora and Suwa Hekiunsai at the Sakai River in 1535, and events leading to Takeda Shingen's invasion of Suwa. While the original manuscript has not been located, a copy made in {{ill|Bunka 14|ja|文化14th year|12=draft}} (1817) has been used for reproductions in historical collections.

