'''Moriya Yorizane''' (守矢 頼真, {{ill|Eishō 2|ja|永正2nd year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Eishō 2|qq=}} {{ill|May 25 (lunar calendar)|ja|5月25日 (旧暦)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/May 25 (lunar calendar)|qq=}} [{{ill|June 26, 1505|ja|1505th year 6月26日|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/June 26, 1505|qq=}}] – {{ill|Keichō 2|ja|慶長2nd year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Keichō 2|qq=}} {{ill|September 10 (lunar calendar)|ja|9月10日 (旧暦)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/September 10 (lunar calendar)|qq=}} [{{ill|October 20, 1597|ja|1597th year 10月20日|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/October 20, 1597|qq=}}]) was a {{ill|Shinto priest|ja|神職|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinto priest|qq=}} during the {{ill|Sengoku period (Japan)|ja|戦国時代 (日本)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sengoku period (Japan)|qq=}}. He served as the {{ill|jinchōkan|ja|神長官|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/jinchōkan|qq=}} (chief priest) of {{ill|Suwa Taisha|ja|諏訪大社|1=Suwa-taisha|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Taisha|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa-taisha|qq=}} in the {{ill|Suwa District, Nagano|ja|諏訪郡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa District, Nagano|qq=}}, {{ill|Shinano Province|ja|信濃国|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinano Province|qq=}}. According to the *{{ill|Suwa Shiryō Sōsho|ja|諏訪史料叢書|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Shiryō Sōsho|qq=}}*<ref>諏訪史料叢書 諏訪教育会著 1925-1952 12巻 守矢頼真書留(守矢頼真) 神長殿知行御検地[https://iss.ndl.go.jp/sp/show/R100000002-I000000871552-00/ 国会図書館]</ref>, he was the son of {{ill|Moriya Ariyoshi|ja|守矢有実|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Moriya Ariyoshi|qq=}}. His son was {{ill|Moriya Nobuzane|ja|守矢信真|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Moriya Nobuzane|qq=}}. His initial name was Yorimitsu<ref>[https://kotobank.jp/word/%E5%AE%88%E7%9F%A2%E9%A0%BC%E5%AE%9F-1794824 コトバンク守矢頼実]参照。</ref>.
== Biography == The {{ill|Moriya clan|ja|守矢氏|1=Moriya clan|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Moriya clan|13=User:Immanuelle/Moriya clan|qq=}} is believed to be descended from either {{ill|Moriya|lt=Moriya|lt=Moreya no Kami|ja|洩矢神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Moreya no Kami|qq=}} or {{ill|Mononobe no Moriya|ja|物部守屋|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mononobe no Moriya|qq=}}, but this remains uncertain. Yorizane served under the {{ill|Suwa clan|ja|諏訪氏|1=Suwa clan|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa clan|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa clan|qq=}}, the {{ill|Hōri|lt=Hōri|lt=Ōhori|ja|大祝|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōhori|qq=}} (chief priests) of Suwa Taisha, and frequently clashed with the {{ill|Negi|ja|禰宜|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Negi|qq=}} {{ill|tayū|ja|太夫|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/tayū|qq=}} Yajima Mitsukiyo. He was initially at a disadvantage but regained his position during the appointment of {{ill|Suwa Yoritaka|ja|諏訪頼高|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Yoritaka|qq=}} as Ōhori in {{ill|Tenbun 7|ja|天文7年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenbun 7|qq=}} (1538). Yorizane also opposed {{ill|Suwa Yorishige (Sengoku period)|ja|諏訪頼重 (戦国時代)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Yorishige (Sengoku period)|qq=}} regarding taxation on Suwa Taisha.
In {{ill|Tenbun 11|ja|天文11年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenbun 11|qq=}} (1542), when {{ill|Takeda Shingen|ja|Takeda Shingen|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takeda Shingen|qq=}} of {{ill|Kai Province|ja|甲斐国|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kai Province|qq=}} initiated his invasion of Suwa, Yorishige was captured and later died. Yorizane supported the Takeda clan’s control of Suwa and earned their trust through rituals and prayers for victory (*{{ill|Moriya Yorizane Shokutō|ja|守矢頼真書留|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Moriya Yorizane Shokutō|qq=}}*). In {{ill|Eiroku 2|ja|永禄2nd year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Eiroku 2|qq=}} (1559), he retired and passed the role of jinchōkan to his son Nobuzane. After the fall of the Takeda clan, Yorizane worked to revive the Suwa clan and contributed to the restoration of Suwa Taisha.
== *Moriya Yorizane Shokutō* == A personal record written by Yorizane, comprising one volume, documents the rituals and management of Suwa Taisha from his father’s era. The surviving entries span from {{ill|Tenbun 11|ja|天文11年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenbun 11|qq=}} (1542) to {{ill|Tenbun 21|ja|天文21st year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenbun 21|qq=}} (1552). It includes key historical events, such as the birth of Yorishige’s heir in April 1542 and Yorishige’s death in July. While it initially covers the Takeda invasion of Suwa, later entries focus on shrine administration. The original manuscript was preserved by the Moriya family, and its text has been reproduced in collections such as the *{{ill|Shinano Shiryō Sōsho|ja|信濃史料叢書|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinano Shiryō Sōsho|qq=}}* and the *{{ill|Yamanashi Prefectural History|ja|山梨県史|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamanashi Prefectural History|qq=}}*.
== *Shinshi Ontō no Nikki* == A record of the shrine's annual rituals and notable events from {{ill|Kyōroku 1|ja|享禄元年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyōroku 1|qq=}} (1528) to {{ill|Tenbun 23|ja|天文23rd year|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenbun 23|qq=}} (1554). It describes significant occurrences, such as the peace negotiations between Takeda Nobutora and Suwa Hekiunsai at the Sakai River in 1535, and events leading to Takeda Shingen's invasion of Suwa. While the original manuscript has not been located, a copy made in {{ill|Bunka 14|ja|文化14年|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bunka 14|qq=}} (1817) has been used for reproductions in historical collections.
